<?php $__env->startSection('content'); ?><p>Olympic chiefs have confirmed they are in talks about limiting the number of fans at next summer's rearranged Tokyo Games.</p>

<p>At a Tokyo 2020 executive board meeting on Tuesday, organising committee chief executive Toshiro Muto admitted they are close approving '50 to 60' items to simplify the event and cut costs.</p>

<p>And Muto also said that the issue of spectators is currently being discussed, although no decision is expected until the New Year.</p>

<p>Restrictions on fans was discussed at a Tokyo 2020 executive board meeting on Tuesday</p>

<p>'When it comes to the specific numbers and how much of the percentage of total capacity should be allowed, I can't say whether that will be decided by December,' said Muto.</p>

<p>'We need to keep a close eye on the situation with the Covid-19 spread. We shouldn't make a decision right before Games time, but definitely we should observe the situation thoroughly.'</p>

<p>Capacity at professional sports events in Japan is currently limited to a maximum of 5,000.Â </p>
